## 6. Debugging History & Failure Modes

Freshness: ✅ High — each listed failure was reproduced or covered before resolution.

- An obsolete `tree-sitter` egg and current LlamaIndex APIs conflicted; compatible `tree-sitter-language-pack` and Voyage versions were pinned.
- Initial `uv sync` failed because package metadata referenced a missing README; adding complete package documentation fixed the build.
- Qdrant rejected arbitrary point IDs; deterministic UUID5 IDs fixed storage while retaining the logical chunk ID in metadata.
- Lifecycle callbacks could act on a repository after job reassociation; live job/repository association and lease checks now guard terminal mutation.
- A worker could wait on the repository lock long enough to hold an aging lease; it now renews immediately after acquiring the lock.
- Readiness once inferred worker availability from configuration; it now checks actual inline-worker liveness.
- Old collection cleanup initially assumed the current prefix; UUID-marker discovery handles configuration prefix changes.
- Delete could verify only the configured target; it now verifies all exact physical targets before manifest removal.
- Ready state could outlive physical Qdrant data; question answering returns `INDEX_MISSING`, and startup/stale recovery corrects state rather than serving empty results.
- OpenAI answer status was coupled to embedding construction; answer-provider construction and operational status are independent.
- Provider output could invent or omit citations; server-side citation validation and extractive fallback prevent unsupported attribution.
- The in-app browser cannot control native file inputs; actual API upload plus actual UI lifecycle proof was used and the remaining single-session Playwright evidence is recorded as P4.
- Docker was initially unavailable, then became available through Colima; Compose validation, image build, runtime readiness, health status, and shutdown were all completed before claiming container proof.

